        "text": "Since Durkheim and Weber, some progress has been made in the question of where norms come from and what makes them valid, even if, as the contrast between Habermas' communication theory and Luhmann's \"functionalist interpretation\" shows, there is no consensus within the field. However, despite the opposition of both positions, they agree that norms have a status transcendent to action or communication. (Those who do not like the metaphysical form of expression can say, without changing anything in the matter, that norms are situated on a higher level of emergence than the actions or communications normed by them). To catch up with them was and is an unattained - and one will see: unattainable - goal of economic theory. The most sophisticated attempts to derive norms rationalistically come from game theory (co-founded by Morgenstern).\" But even if one allows the introduction of empirically improbable \"marginal\" conditions, such as an unlimited duration of the game, it does not succeed in solving the problem of cooperation without appealing to either a first blindly trusting act or a generalized other."
